To begin with, we will assume that the metric on $Y$ is split with signature $(7,7)$ (rather than $(9,5)$ which can be worked out by the interested reader) as it is more balanced and appears to lend itself better to both some complex and Clifford Algebra techniques.

Here the split signature Clifford algebra is of Real type and is equivalent to Real 128 square matrices with some additional structure:

$$
\mathrm{Cl}_{7,7} \cong \mathbb{R}(128)
$$

This in turn leads to representations for the Spin group of the form:

$$
\operatorname{Spin}(7,7) \longrightarrow \mathrm{SO}(64,64) \longrightarrow \mathrm{U}(64,64)
$$

so in full generality, all spin representations in $(7,7)$ signature are subsumed by:

$$
\rho_{\text {Spin }}: \operatorname{Spin}(14, \mathbb{C}) \longrightarrow \mathrm{U}(128, \mathbb{C})
$$

The additional structure on these matrix algebras gives them a transpose operation from combining the canonical automorphism of the Clifford algebras (by replacing the generating tetrad with its negative) and the canonical antiautomorphism gotten from reversing the order of basis factors within the various Clifford products.

This leads to concrete models for a number of Lie algebras at the level of Clifford Algebras as in:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathfrak{s o}(7,7) "=" \Lambda^{2} \subset \mathrm{Cl}_{\mathbb{R}(7,7)} \\
\mathfrak{g l}(64, \mathbb{R}) "=" \left(\Lambda^{2} \oplus \Lambda^{6} \oplus \Lambda^{10} \oplus \Lambda^{14}\right) \subset \mathrm{Cl}_{\mathbb{R}(7,7)}
\end{gathered}
$$

As the Left and Right real Weyl spinors transform as 64-dimensional dual defining representations under the General Linear group $\mathrm{GL}(64, \mathbb{R})$, we can form a metric on the space of total Majorana Spinors

$$
\mathscr{G}_{\mathbb{R}}=\mathscr{G}_{\mathbb{R}}^{L} \oplus \mathscr{G}_{\mathbb{R}}^{R}=\mathscr{G}_{\mathbb{R}}^{L} \oplus\left(\mathscr{G}_{\mathbb{R}}^{L}\right)^{*}
$$

according to

$$
<\psi^{L}+\psi^{R}, \sigma^{L}+\sigma^{R}>=\psi^{L}\left(\sigma^{R}\right)+\sigma^{L}\left(\psi^{R}\right)
$$

giving us a split signature metric in which both spaces of Weyl spinors are null as for Weyl Spinors we have:

$$
\stackrel{\text { Structure Group }}{\operatorname{Spin}(7,7)} \longrightarrow \stackrel{\text { Weyl-Left }}{\operatorname{Gl}(64, \mathbb{R})_{+}} \times \stackrel{\text { Weyl-Right }}{\operatorname{Gl}(64, \mathbb{R})_{-}} \longrightarrow \stackrel{\text { Dirac }}{\operatorname{Gl}(128, \mathbb{C})}
$$

The metric for the total Majorana spinors corresponds to the Lie Algebra:

$$
\mathfrak{s o}(64,64) "=" \frac{\left(\Lambda^{2} \oplus \Lambda^{6} \oplus \Lambda^{10} \oplus \Lambda^{14}\right)}{\mathscr{G}_{L} \oplus \mathscr{G}_{R}=\mathscr{G}_{L} \oplus \mathscr{G}_{L}^{*}=\mathscr{G}_{R}^{*} \oplus \mathscr{G}_{R}} \oplus\left(\begin{array}{c}
